                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">If your group is geared similarly to you, you will have to be incredibly careful. It is doable with good players of course. I would get ND for extra HPs, LR is great like you say for defensive aas.  
<br />

<br />
You can pull most dungeons with singles or doubles without pacify, your warr can do mostly if you like, or your sk/necro can fd test rooms if you need.  This should help as you wont have to mez as much, and as you are probably a large chuck of dps for your group it saves you mana to control your pet, and you will need your pet. By and large you will be a mage, and your shaman BST will help you with CC.  TD3 will help, and i am a beliver in CHA.
<br />

<br />
I play my enchanter and box my cleric in Hard adventures.  On pet breaks i have quick assist with cleric and use Sound of might .8 second cast stun, its really an amazing cleric spell that is underused imo.  That might help you control your pet. I wouldnt reccomend hasting it, unless you really need the dps for boss or such.
<br />

<br />
You can pacify blue mobs, i dont do it often, but if your puller says hey this room looks really bad, give it a shot.  Use bind site on an FDer or on mob in room to target. Just great tip in general.
<br />

<br />
Hard adventures are meant to be hard. Communicate who is on what when you pull 2+ so you have automatic target for mez, roots, slows. You can have you Sk taunt one away to give you time to mez perhaps.  Stand away from the incoming mobs on pulls, they hate enchanters instinctively i think ...
<br />

<br />
If you are having fun trying hards, keep trying it! You will figure it out . Losses are meaningless.  Being challenged and having fun is key !</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=472453" target="_blank" class="postlink">Clarsah Silverspoon Coercer of Ascent</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
