                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hasting/dualwielding the pet on hard really is not worth the additional risk and hassle, imo. As long as I can get a pet, we clear a hard dungeon in 40-50 minutes usually. My personal record is 31 minutes on a hard assassinate, first mob we found was pet then. You can shave off max 5-10 minutes by hasting/dualwielding the pet, but at a big increase in risk.
<br />

<br />
Dungeons with no pet sucks  <img src="images/smiles/icon_cry.gif" alt="icon_cry.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
The key to proceeding fast is low downtime. I usually scout next room while the damage team whack down the current targets, then the tank can pull immediately on my instructions. The tank will do the actual pull unless I do mez pull or it is an obvious single. If you get two beating on you you are usually fairly dead.
<br />

<br />
Sending in pet first is a good tactic, it works well in situations where you can move up to the mob. Pet also can pull off you if you get aggro from failed mezzes etc.
<br />

<br />
Usually most of a hard dungeon is fairly trivial pull-wise. There usually is 2-3 challenging spots where you can get bad multipulls. We usually just let the tank pull those, but try to pull as few as possible. I haven't found pacify very useful, too much resists. I only risk pacify when we would get REALLY big pull otherwise.
<br />

<br />
Having a mez target pretargeted on pull helps a lot. If you get much mez resists CHA will help somewhat, the tests that has been done showed CHA has most effect on mobs that are close to or above your level.
<br />

<br />
Having Divine Arbitration on the cleric seems useful too  <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
I have LR5 and ID5.. and they have a very noticeable effect.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
