                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-style: italic">Heheh ehe Hard... dont bother unless you have VT + gear real</span>
<br />

<br />
Actually you don't need VT+ gear, and in fact, it's quite worth it, even if you aren't going for points.  Some of the items that drop from nameds in hards are decent upgrades to many folks who aren't hardcore raiding or who haven't gotten their shot at VT or elemental planes.
<br />

<br />
There are folks who will happily trigger hards, track for a name, and clear to it rather than doing the adventure.
<br />

<br />

<br />
As for tactics, pacification is rarely useful in hards.  We have a bard pull when my group does hards.  Every now and then he gets skished on a bad pull, but overall, give your party pre-targets.  Have them fire root/mez/whatever CC they can and sort stuff out from there with mez or charm-pet tanking.
<br />

<br />
Charm is key.  It's not required to win, but the hitpoints on mobs in a hard for an "underequiped" group make your chance of victory much higher if you can find something to charm.
<br />

<br />
Unfortunately, it's not always possible to find a charmable pet, much to my anger.
<br />

<br />
The posts above on using charmed pets buffed to the teeth are worthwhile if your group is willing to make you the 'star' and play in what is probably an atypical manner for them (and quite possibly a more boring manner for them).  Otherwise just use an unbuffed charmed pet for DPS.  A single 900+ hitting NPC in hards probably more than doubles your group's damage output.
<br />

<br />
Remember also, you have the whole chunk of the dungeon that you've cleared to play with, if you need running room <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
